page.title: 19Birds and Beasts
page.content: Escaped trout, perch, eeel and gudgeon are the common fish. All fishing is coarse. Rudd, roach and dace are fre- quent. All song birds are represen- ted and herons, field fare, corvids, magpies, birds of prey and bats. Visitors include whoopers, and occas- ional Bewicks, mallard, redwing, lap- wings, swifts and martins. Pheasant, quail, and skylarks are much in evid- ence, and the barn owls and Little Owls appear to be recovering in num- bers. Cormorants, buzzards, snipe and nightingales are seen. Feral cats and mink, are found on the moors, with escaped roe deer. Aquatic and land rodents feed foxes. Rabbits and hares cause problems, as do moles. Frogs, toads and elvers process across the moors annually. Insect life is becoming more abundant again. Feral ferrets and their cousins now thrive.
